
[1]rabbet

   RAB'BET, v.t.

   1. To pare down the edge of a board or other piece of timber, for the
   purpose of receiving the edge of another piece by lapping and thus
   uniting the two.

   2. To lap and unite the edges of boards, &c. In ship carpentry, to let
   the edge of a plank into the keel.

    RAB'BET, n. A cut on the side of a board, &c. to fit it to another by
                lapping; a joint made by lapping boards, &c.
